Introduction

Short text description of the study and of the specific data and reanalyses you will be doing, to orient your reader. Outline (briefly!) the goal of the original paper, the data set used, and the analyses conducted, then describe which ones you will replicate.

The mayor objectives of this Replication Data Assignment is to replicate the (1) Summary statistics of soil observations (Table II of the paper), (2) the representation of the pH Values of the Morteratsch valley as a function of time since glacial retreat for observations in the fluvial and stable zones (Figure 5. of the paper), and (3) the correlation between the time since glacial retreat and soil properties, for the stable zone of the pro-glacial areas in all three valleys (Table III of the paper). In addition, and to train myself working with spatial data, I tried to replicate Figure 3., which shows the soil sample location in the three studied valleys.

Therefore, this Rmd document is divided is 4 parts

  1. Visualization of the 3 Study sites and samples Slight modification of figure 3 to reproduce the figure with the available data

  2. Summary statistic Replication of Table II. Summary statistics of soil observations

  3. Descriptive analysis - Visualization of Figure 5: pH Values as a function of time since glacial retreat for observations in the fluvial and stable zones, with potential debris flows in the stable zone separated from the rest of that zone.

3.Linear model Replication of: * Table III. Strength (r) and significance (p (r = 0)) of the correlation between the time since glacial retreat and soil properties, for the stable zone of the pro-glacial areas in all three valleys

1. Summary statistic

  • Table II presents the summary statistics for some numerical attributes of the soils for every pro-glacial valley for the stable and fluvial zones.
## computing summary statistic for the 5 variables of interest: pH, SSD, Vegetation cover, Soil Stoniness and Surface Stoniness, for all observations, and for each site depending of the geomorphological zone (Stable or Fluvial)
  
 #reordering Site to read results with the same order than in the paper (easier to check on data values)

d$Site<-factor(d$Site,levels = c("Forno","Tschierva","Morteratsch"))

Summary<-d%>%
  select(Site, geomorph_zone,pH_field, stoniness_soil, stoniness_surf, veg_cover,SSD)%>%
  group_by(Site, geomorph_zone)%>%
  filter(geomorph_zone=="fluvial"| geomorph_zone== "development")%>%
  summarise(across(c("pH_field", "stoniness_soil", "stoniness_surf", "veg_cover","SSD"),list(Mean=mean, SD=sd),na.rm=TRUE))

## Joining, by = c("pH_field_Mean", "pH_field_SD", "stoniness_soil_Mean", "stoniness_soil_SD", "stoniness_surf_Mean", "stoniness_surf_SD", "veg_cover_Mean", "veg_cover_SD", "SSD_Mean", "SSD_SD")
Counts<-full_join( CountAll,Count,by=NULL)
## Joining, by = "n"

  • Paper’s method: The T-test was used to test for differences in mean soil properties between the different zones in pro-glacial areas. They tested for pH (pH_field), Depth of soil formation (“SSD” = significant soil depth),Vegetation cover (“veg_cover”), Soil Stoniness (“stoniness_soil”), and Surface stoniness (“stoniness_surf”). The standard deviation was also computed.
# Computing the P-Value of the T-test

d<-d%>%filter(geomorph_zone=="fluvial"|geomorph_zone=="development")%>%filter(pH_field!='na')


Table_p_values<-tibble(Site=character(),
                variable=character(),
                p=numeric())

Site<-unique(d$Site)

df<-d%>%select(pH_field, veg_cover, stoniness_soil, stoniness_surf)

Site<-unique(d$Site)
for (i in Site){
   for (j in names(df)){
     #print(j)
 temp<-d %>% filter(Site==i)%>%select(j, geomorph_zone)
 print(nrow(temp))
 p<-t.test(temp[[j]]~temp$geomorph_zone)$p.value
 #print(p)
 r<- tibble(Site=i,variable=j,p=p)
 Table_p_values<-bind_rows(Table_p_values,r)
}}

2. Descriptive analysis - Visualization of Figure 5: pH Values as a function of time since glacial retreat for observations in the fluvial and stable zones, with potential debris flows in the stable zone separated from the rest of that zone.

# Creating a new data set to remove "slope" and "none" values of the [geomorh_zone variable]
d_stability_Forno<-d%>%filter(Site=="Forno")%>% ###COMMENTS : It took me a very long while to understand the graph was only including the Forno data set!
  filter(geomorph_zone!="none")%>%
  filter(geomorph_zone!="slope")

# Creating a new variable call stability
d_stability_Forno<-d_stability_Forno%>%
  mutate(stability=case_when(
    geomorph_zone=="development" & potential_dist=="debris flow"~"stable-debris",
    geomorph_zone=="development"~"stable",
    geomorph_zone=="fluvial"~"fluvial"))

#View(d_stability_Forno)

# Reordering the stability variable
d_stability_Forno$stability<-factor(d_stability_Forno$stability,levels=c("stable-debris", "stable","fluvial"))

# Plotting pH in function of time since glacier retreat , and grouping by stability

pH_time<-ggplot(d_stability_Forno, aes(y=pH_field, x=realTSR, color=stability)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=stability), size=3) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('hotpink3','darkgreen','deepskyblue3'))+
  theme_bw()+ 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,120),ylim=c(4,8)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100,120))+
  labs(x="time since glacial retreat (y)", y="pH") +
  theme_bw()
pH_time

* On this first version of the graph we observe three differences with the original graph of the paper. One fluvial point is missing from the data base and one points (top right) appear as stable and should be a fluvial point, as weel its neighboor that is also stable and should be stable-debris.

Below we look at the same graph but using different shapes to draw the pH values. Here, we notice that F27 and F29 where superposed. The blue fluvial F27 was hidden by the green stable 29.

pH_time<-ggplot(d_stability_Forno, aes(y=pH_field, x=realTSR, color=stability)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape=stability,color=stability), size=3) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('hotpink3','darkgreen','deepskyblue3'))+

However, there is still a difference according F28 that appear as stable-debris (red) on the original figure in Figure 5, and as stable (green) in our graph. And one other fluvial point between F24 and F22 is missing.

Looking again a the dataset shared by the authors, there is another dataset tab, called All_export. The data of this data set is identic to the Site dataset, but except for the variable Potential disturbance where the point F28 is considered as debris flow instead of NA.

Below the same code is run with this alternative data set called “All Export”.

This disagreement might be what also cause the different results observed in the Summary table.But we have the same count of observation, so this is still questionable.

Now only an error with F23 which appear with “slope” in the both dataset, but as “fluvial” in the graph of the paper.

    Table_pearson<-bind_rows(Table_pearson,results)
  }}
